>Austin</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Dallas</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Houston</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">San Antonio</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Atlanta</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Nashville</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/05/22/multimedia/22xp-waymo-bvwl/22xp-waymo-bvwl-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Loren Elliott for The New York Times</media:credit><media:description>Waymo also announced it was temporarily halting its highway service this week to improve its navigation system. </media:description></media:content></item><item><title>Meta Settles a School District’s Social Media Addiction Lawsuit</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/05/21/technology/meta-settlement-social-media-addiction-lawsuit.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/05/21/technology/meta-settlement-social-media-addiction-lawsuit.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/05/21/technology/meta-settlement-social-media-addiction-lawsuit.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>Snap, TikTok and YouTube had already settled with the Kentucky district, allowing the companies to avert the first in a series of federal trials.</description><dc:creator>Cecilia Kang</dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 21 May 2026 20:21:02 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Meta</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Lawsuits</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Compensatory Damages</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Victim Compensation</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Social Media</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Addiction</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Teens</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Mental Health</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Product liability</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Snap</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Snapchat</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">TikTok</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">YouTube</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Kentucky</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">K-12 Education</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/05/21/multimedia/HFO-SOCIALMEDIA-SETTLEMENT-1-tflw/HFO-SOCIALMEDIA-SETTLEMENT-1-tflw-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Kenny Holston/The New York Times</media:credit><media:description>Meta, led by Mark Zuckerberg, shown at the U.S. Capitol in March, lost jury verdicts that month in two similar lawsuits.</media:description></media:content></item><item><title>How Google Is Starting to Win the A.I. Race</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/05/19/technology/personaltech/google-gemini-ai.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/05/19/technology/personaltech/google-gemini-ai.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/05/19/technology/personaltech/google-gemini-ai.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>Despite its early stumbles, Google’s Gemini has leapfrogged ChatGPT in relevance and usefulness. Soon, it will be ubiquitous.</description><dc:creator>Brian X. Chen</dc:creator><pubDate>Tue, 19 May 2026 17:45:06 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Google</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">ChatGPT</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Online advertising</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Anthropic</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">OpenAI</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/05/21/business/19techfix/19techfix-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Sisi Yu</media:credit></media:content></item><item><title>Why Your Life Is Now on Subscriptions</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/05/12/business/subscriptions-products-services.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/05/12/business/subscriptions-products-services.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/05/12/business/subscriptions-products-services.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>As companies look to build cash flow and loyalty, everything from heated car seats to earthworm deliveries can become a recurring charge on your credit card.</description><dc:creator>Sopan Deb</dc:creator><pubDate>Tue, 12 May 2026 09:00:59 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">US</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">E Commerce</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computers and the Internet</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Tech Industry</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Mobile Apps</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Price</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Consumer behaviour</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">advertising</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">marketing</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Cars</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Electric Cars and Hybrids</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/05/06/multimedia/00xp-subscriptions-ptvf/00xp-subscriptions-ptvf-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Nam Y. Huh/Associated Press</media:credit><media:description>From streaming services to car features, more companies are moving toward a model that turns customers into lifelong subscribers.</media:description></media:content></item><item><title>Google Appeals Landmark Ruling Declaring It a Monopolist in Search</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/05/22/technology/google-appeals-search-case.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/05/22/technology/google-appeals-search-case.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/05/22/technology/google-appeals-search-case.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>Google asked a federal appeals court on Friday to reverse a judge’s ruling that it had violated antitrust laws, as well as a requirement it share some data with rivals.</description><dc:creator>David McCabe</dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 22 May 2026 16:34:58 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Google</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Competition law</category><category domai